    "id": "23718fee",
    "skill": "Cross-Text Connections",
    "difficulty": "Medium",
    "passage": "Text 1\nFor decades, bluegrass musicians have debated whether their genre should exclude influences from mainstream genres such as\nrock. Many insist that bluegrass is defined by its adherence to the folk music of the US South, out of which bluegrass emerged.\nSuch \u201cpurists,\u201d as they are known, regard the recordings of Bill Monroe, which established the bluegrass sound in the 1940s, as a\nstandard against which the genre should still be measured.\n\u00a0\nText 2\nBluegrass isn\u2019t simply an extension of folk traditions into the era of recorded music. In reality, Bill Monroe created the bluegrass\nsound in the 1940s by combining Southern folk music with commercial genres that had arisen only a few decades before, such as\njazz and the blues. Since bluegrass has always been a mixed genre, contemporary bluegrass musicians should not be forbidden\nfrom incorporating into it influences from rock and other mainstream genres.",
    "question": "Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely regard the perspective of bluegrass purists, as described in Text 1?",
